{{refbegin}}

* {{note|a|a}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Alif}}'' can represent many phonemes in [[Literary Arabic]]:
*# Without [[Arabic diacritics|diacritics]]: {{lower|0.5em|2=<span style="font-size:300%">{{lang|ar|ا}}</span>}}
*#* initially: ''{{transl|ar|DIN|a, i}}'' &nbsp; {{IPA|/a, i/}} or sometimes silent in the definite article {{lang|ar|ال}} ''[[al-|{{transl|ar|ALA|(a)l-}}]]''
*#* medially or finally: ''{{transl|ar|ALA|ā}}'' &nbsp; {{IPA|/aː/}}.
*# ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Alif}}'' with ''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}]]'' above:  {{lower|0.6em|2=<span style="font-size:300%;line-height:100%">{{lang|ar|أ}}</span>}}
*#* initially:  ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾa, ʾu}}'' &nbsp; {{IPA|/ʔa, ʔu/}}
*#* medially or finally: ''{{transl|ar|DIN|aʾ}}'' &nbsp; {{IPA|/ʔa/}}.
*# ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Alif}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}'' under: {{raise|0.3em|2=<span style="font-size:300%;line-height:90%">{{lang|ar|إ}}</span>}}
*#* initially: ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾi}}'' &nbsp; {{IPA|/ʔi/}}; doesn't appear medially or finally (see [[hamza]]).
*# ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Alif}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|ALA|maddah&#x202f;}}'':  {{lower|0.5em|2=<span style="font-size:300%;line-height:90%">{{lang|ar|آ}}</span>}}
*#* initially, medially or finally: ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾā}}'' &nbsp; {{IPA|/ʔaː/}}.

* {{note|b|b}} {{IPAslink|p}} and {{IPAslink|v}} can be represented by <span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[پ]]}}</span> and <span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ڤ]]}}</span>&lrm;/<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|ڥ}}</span> or if unavailable, <span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ب]]}}</span> and <span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ف]]}}</span>&lrm;/<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|ڢ}}</span> are used, respectively. The letters {{script/Arabic|[[ب]]}} and {{script/Arabic|[[ف]]}} can also be used for {{lower|0.1em|2={{IPAslink|p}}}} and {{lower|0.1em|2={{IPAslink|v}}}}, or the letters {{script/Arabic|[[پ]]}} and {{script/Arabic|[[ڤ]]}} can be used in Egypt.

*{{note|c|c}} For Arabic language speakers, the phoneme {{IPAslink|ɡ}} can be represented using different letters, depending on [[varieties of Arabic|local dialects]]. {{raise|0.2em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ج]]}}</span>}} is normally used in Egypt, also sometimes Yemen and Oman. {{raise|0.3em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ق]]}}</span>}} is used where it represents the {{IPAblink|ɡ}} in local dialects. {{lower|0.3em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ك]]}}</span>}} or {{lower|0.15em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[غ]]}}</span>}} are used where {{IPAslink|ɡ}} doesn't exist in local dialects. Other letters such as {{lower|0.65em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[گ]]}}</span>}},&lrm; {{lower|0.65em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ݣ]]}}</span>}} or <span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|ڨ}}</span> may also be used, but are not regarded as standard Arabic letters. Likewise, where {{script/Arabic|[[ج]]}} represents {{IPAblink|ɡ}}, it can be also used for {{lower|0.1em|2={{IPAslink|ʒ}}}}~{{lower|0.2em|2={{IPAslink|d͡ʒ}}}}, or the letter {{raise|0.3em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[چ]]}}</span>}} can be used in Egypt.

* {{note|d|d}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Fā’}}'' and ''{{transl|ar|ALA|qāf}}'' are traditionally written in [[Maghreb|northwestern Africa]] as {{lower|0.1em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|ڢ}}</span>}} and {{lower|0.2em|2=<span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|ڧـ ـڧـ ـٯ}}</span>}}, respectively, while the latter's dot is only added initially or medially.

* {{note|e|e}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Yā’}}'' in the isolated and the final forms in handwriting and print in Egypt, Sudan and sometimes other places, is always undotted <span style="font-size:x-large">{{script/Arabic|[[ى]]}}</span>, making it only contextually distinguishable from ''{{transl|ar|ALA|alif maqṣūrah}}''.

{{refend}}

See also [[#Additional letters|Additional letters]] below.

====Further notes====
* The letter ''{{transl|ar|ALA|alif}}'' originated in the [[Phoenician alphabet]] as a consonant-sign indicating a glottal stop. Today it has lost its function as a consonant, and, together with  ''{{transl|ar|ALA|ya’}}'' and  ''{{transl|ar|ALA|wāw}}'', is a ''[[mater lectionis]]'', a consonant sign standing in for a long vowel (see below), or as support for certain diacritics (''{{transl|ar|ALA|maddah}}'' and ''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}]]'').

* Arabic currently uses a [[diacritic]] sign, <span style="font-size:150%;"> {{lang|ar|ﺀ}}</span>, called ''{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}'', to denote the [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[ʔ]}}, written alone or with a carrier:
** alone: {{lang|ar|ء}}
** with a carrier: {{lang|ar|إ أ}} (above or under a ''{{transl|ar|ALA|alif}}''), {{lang|ar|ؤ}} (above a ''{{transl|ar|ALA|wāw}}''), {{lang|ar|ئ}} (above a dotless ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’}}''  or ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’ hamzah}}'').

In academic work, the ''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}]]'' ({{lang|ar|ء}}) is transliterated with the [[modifier letter right half ring]]  (ʾ), while the [[modifier letter left half ring]] (ʿ) transliterates the letter ''[[Ayin|{{transl|ar|ALA|‘ayn}}]]'' ({{lang|ar|ع}}), which represents a different sound, not found in English.

* Letters lacking an initial or medial version are never linked to the letter that follows, even within a word. The ''{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}'' has a single form, since it is never linked to a preceding or following letter.  However, it is sometimes combined with a ''{{transl|ar|ALA|wāw}}'', ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’}}'', or ''{{transl|ar|ALA|alif}}'', and in that case the carrier behaves like an ordinary ''{{transl|ar|ALA|wāw}}'', ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’}}'', or ''{{transl|ar|ALA|alif}}''.

* The shape of the final ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’}}'' is always undotted <big>{{lang|ar|[[ى]]}}</big> in both print and handwriting in Egypt and Sudan, mainly.

====Modified letters====
The following are not individual letters, but rather different contextual variants of some of the Arabic letters.

