===Vowel omission===
An Arabic [[syllable]] can be open (ending with a vowel) or closed (ending with a consonant):

* open: CV [consonant-vowel] (long or short vowel)
* closed: CVC (short vowel only)

A normal text is composed only of a series of consonants plus vowel-lengthening letters; thus, the word ''{{transl|ar|ALA|qalb}}'', "heart", is written ''{{transl|ar|qlb}}'', and the word ''{{transl|ar|ALA|qalab}}'', "he turned around", is also written ''{{transl|ar|qlb}}''. 

To write qalab without this ambiguity, we could indicate that the l is followed by a short 'a' by writing a fatha above it.

To write qalb, we would instead indicate that the l is followed by no vowel by marking it with a [[diacritic]] called ''{{transl|ar|ALA|sukūn}}'' ( {{script/Arabic|  ْ  }} &nbsp;), like this: {{lang|ar|قلْبْ}}).

This is one step down from full vocalization, where the vowel after the q would also be indicated by a''{{transl|ar|ALA|fatḥah}}'': {{lang|ar|قَلْبْ}}.

The ''{{transl|ar|ALA|[[Qur’ān]]}}'' is traditionally written in full vocalization. 

The long i sound in some qurans is written with a kasra followed diacriticless ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’}}'', and long u by a damma followed by a bare ''{{transl|ar|ALA|wāw}}''. In other qurans, this ya and this waw carry a ''{{transl|ar|ALA|sukūn}}''. Outside of the ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Qur’ān}}'', the latter convention is extremely rare, to the point that ''{{transl|ar|ALA|yā’}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|ALA|sukūn}}'' will be unambiguously read as the [[diphthong]] {{IPA|/aj/}}, and ''{{transl|ar|ALA|wāw}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|ALA|sukūn}}'' will be read {{IPA|/aw/}}. 

For example, the letters ''{{transl|ar|m-y-l}}'' can be read like English meel or like English mail, or (theoretically) also some other ways, like 'mayyal' or 'mayil'. But if a sukuun is added on the ya' then the miim cannot have a sukuun (because two letters in a row cannot be sukunated), cannot have a damma (because there is never an 'uy' sound in Arabic unless there is another vowel after the ya), and cannot have a kasra (because kasra before sukunated ya' is never found outside qurans), so it MUST have a fatha and the only possible pronunciation is /mayl/ (meaning mile, or even e-mail). By the same token, m-y-t with a sukoon over the y can be mayt but not mayyit or meet, and m-w-t with a sukoon on the w can only be mawt, not moot (iw is impossible when the w closes the syllable).

Vowel marks are always written as if  the ''[[’I‘rab|{{transl|ar|ALA|i‘rāb}}]]'' vowels were in fact pronounced, even when they must be skipped in actual pronunciation. So, when writing the name ''{{transl|ar|Aḥmad}}'', it is optional to place a sukoon on the ''{{transl|ar|ḥ}}'', but a sukoon is forbidden on the ''{{transl|ar|d}}'', because that d would carry a damma if any other word followed, as in ''{{transl|ar|Aḥmadu zawjī}}'' meaning "Ahmad is my husband".

Another example: the sentence that in correct Arabic must be pronounced ''{{transl|ar|Aḥmadu zawjun sharrīr}}'', meaning "Ahmed is a wicked husband", is usually mispronounced as ''{{transl|ar|Aḥmad zawj sharrīr}}''. Yet, for the purposes of Arabic grammar and orthography, is treated as if it were not mispronounced and as if yet another word followed it, i.e., if adding any vowel marks, they must be added as if the pronunciation were ''{{transl|ar|Aḥmadu zawjun sharrīrun}}'' with a tanween 'un' at the very end. So, it is correct to add an 'un' tanween sign on the final r, but actually pronouncing it would be a hypercorrection. Also, it is never correct to write a sukoon on that r, even though in actual pronunciation that r is (and in correct Arabic MUST be) sukooned.

Of course, if the correct i`râb is a sukuun, it may be optionally written.

