The ''{{transl|ar|ALA|sukūn}}'' is also used for transliterating words into the Arabic script. The Persian word {{lang|fa|ماسک}} (''mâsk'', from the English word "mask"), for example, might be written with a ''{{transl|ar|ALA|sukūn}}'' above the {{lang|fa|ﺱ}}  to signify that there is no vowel sound between that letter and the {{lang|fa|ک}}.

==Additional letters==<!--If any are missing, please add them.-->
<!-- This would look nicer in tables. -->

===Regional variations===
*<big>{{script/Arabic|ڢ}}</big> – a [[Pe (letter)#Arabic fa|Maghrebi]] variation of the letter {{lang|ar|ف}} (''{{transl|ar|ALA|fā’}}'') .

*<big>{{script/Arabic|ٯ}}</big> and <big>{{script/Arabic|ڧ}}</big> – a [[ق#Arabic qaf|Maghrebi]] variation of standard letter {{script/Arabic|ق}} (as a rule, dotless in isolated and final positions and dotted in the initial and medial forms {{script/Arabic|ڧـ ـڧـ ـٯ}}).

Additional modified letters, used in non-Arabic languages, or in Arabic for transliterating names, loanwords, [[varieties of Arabic|spoken dialects]] only, include:

===Sometimes used for writing names, loanwords and dialects===
*<big>{{script/Arabic|[[Ve (Arabic letter)|ڤ]]}}</big> – (not to be confused with <big>{{script/Arabic|ڨ}}</big>) used in [[Kurdish language]] when written in [[Arabic script]] and sometimes used in Arabic language to represent the sound {{IPAslink|v}} when transliterating names and loanwords in Arabic. Also used in writing [[Varieties of Arabic|dialects]] with that sound.<ref name=dialecttutorial>[http://www1.ccls.columbia.edu/~cadim/ArabicDialectTutorialAMTA2006.pdf Arabic Dialect Tutorial]</ref> (Usually the letter <big>{{lang|ar|[[ف]]}}</big> (''{{transl|ar|fā’}}'') transliterates {{IPAslink|v}}.) Also used as ''pa'' in the [[Jawi script]]. The phoneme {{IPAslink|v}} in Tunisia and some other regions of Maghreb is rendered using <big>{{script/Arabic|ڥ}}</big>.
<!--If any, add more languages. -->

*<big>{{script/Arabic|[[Pe (Persian letter)|پ]]}}</big> – used to represent the phoneme {{IPAslink|p}} in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], and [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]]; sometimes used in Arabic language when transliterating names and loanwords, although Arabic mostly substitutes {{IPAslink|b}} for {{IPAslink|p}} in the transliteration of names and loanwords. So, "[[7up]]" can be transcribed as <big>{{lang|ar|سفن&nbsp;أب}}</big> or <big>{{script/Arabic|سڤن&nbsp;أﭖ}}</big>.
<!--If any, add more languages. -->

*<big>{{script/Arabic|[[Che (Persian letter)|چ]]}}</big> – used to represent {{IPAslink|t͡ʃ}} ("ch"). It is used in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], and [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] and sometimes used when transliterating names and loanwords in Arabic. In the [[Iraqi Arabic|Iraqi spoken dialect]] it may be used, especially when referring in the feminine, although it is rarely written, as well as rarely used in the Maghrebi spelling.  Nevertheless, Arabic usually substitutes other letters in the transliteration of names and loanwords: normally the combination <big>{{lang|ar|تش}}</big> (''{{transl|ar|ALA|tā’}}''-''{{transl|ar|ALA|shīn}}'') is used to transliterate the {{IPAslink|t͡ʃ}}, as in "[[Chad]]". In Egypt <big>{{script/Arabic|چ}}</big> is used for {{IPAslink|ʒ}} (or {{IPAslink|d͡ʒ}}, which is approximated to {{IPAblink|ʒ}}). In Israel, it's used to render {{IPAslink|ɡ}} in Arabic language, for example on roadsigns.
**''Ca'' in the [[Jawi script]].<!--If any, add more languages. -->

*<big>{{script/Arabic|[[گ]]}}</big> – used to represent {{IPAslink|ɡ}}. Normally used in [[Persian alphabet|Persian]], [[Kurdish alphabet|Kurdish]], and [[Urdu language|Urdu]].<ref name=dialecttutorial/> Often names and loanwords with {{IPAslink|ɡ}} are transliterated in Arabic with <big>{{lang|ar|[[ك]]}}</big> (''{{transl|ar|ALA|kāf}}''), <big>{{lang|ar|[[ق]]}}</big> (''{{transl|ar|ALA|qāf}}''), <big>{{lang|ar|[[غ]]}}</big> (''{{transl|ar|ALA|ghayn}}'') or <big>{{lang|ar|[[ج]]}}</big> (''{{transl|ar|jīm}}''), which may or may not change the original sound. In Egypt <big>{{lang|ar|ج}}</big> is normally pronounced {{IPAblink|ɡ}}.
<!--If any, add more languages. -->

*<big>{{script/Arabic|ڨ}}</big><!--[[File:Tunisian-gaf.svg|14px]]--> – a Maghrebi letter, sometimes used for {{IPAblink|ɡ}} (not to be confused with <big>{{script/Arabic|ڤ}}</big>).  In [[Tunisia]] it is sometimes used to represent the phoneme {{IPAslink|ɡ}}. In final and isolate form it has the form which resembles the letter <big>{{lang|ar|ق}}</big> ''{{transl|ar|ALA|qāf}}'' whence it derives.

*<big>{{script/Arabic|ڜ}}</big> – a Maghrebi letter for {{IPAblink|t͡ʃ}}.

